snippet.textDisplay: Have we become so shallow that we can not engage in conversation about actual events. Gayle King did not disrespect Kobe, she asked a friend of Kobe if his legacy is complicated and pointed out that she most likely would not be in a place to see such behavior because she was his friend. How many of us have done things when our friends are not around, that  would surprise them if they saw us doing them?   To make the leap that this is disrespectful belittles our intelligence as it seems to indicate an inability to go beyond the surface of a thought or idea. This immediate leap to outrage and attack is unfortunate. Unfortunate because it will be used as fuel to fan the flame of division at a time when a need for solidarity is most important. Don't be blinded and made deaf by the loud cry of outrage because someone asked a question that requires some reflection and acknowledgement of factual events. Let's not be played by the wizards controlling the messages and narratives sent  across the airwaves. Being conditioned to make leaps like these with little reflection and acknowledgement that only the tip of an iceberg is seen at the surface. Will lead to a people that will act in haste and be lead to division that will serve only those who wish to keep the crabs strong so they will have strength.

snippet.textDisplay: Me personally , I am not asking about a dead mans allegations , especially if he was acquitted... I do think after watching Gayle did not come from place of love.  She came with questions that she wanted answers . It's her job( bread and butter) which we must understand as community. How many times as black people have we been in the work environment and we watched our coworkers be thrown to the wolves because the job had an agenda.
